  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_863918627" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/863918627" />
    <a title="Cat" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/78792-cat"><img alt="Cat" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1199044332p2/78792.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/863918627?book_show_action=true">Feb 24, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cat" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cat" href="/user/show/78792-cat">Cat</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer863918627" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12588995670484625455">I did not know anything about the Bhopal tragedy before reading this book, and in spite of its fictionalization here, the visceral realities of living in a poisoned community with little to no recourse or restitution are absolutely vivid. Through his protagonist and narrator, Animal, a young man whose spine was misshapen by exposure to the chemical leak, who runs on all fours with strong arms and hears voices, Sinha vivifies the textures of life permeated by toxicity and loss. When Animal hides </span>
  <span id="freeText12588995670484625455" style="display:none">I did not know anything about the Bhopal tragedy before reading this book, and in spite of its fictionalization here, the visceral realities of living in a poisoned community with little to no recourse or restitution are absolutely vivid. Through his protagonist and narrator, Animal, a young man whose spine was misshapen by exposure to the chemical leak, who runs on all fours with strong arms and hears voices, Sinha vivifies the textures of life permeated by toxicity and loss. When Animal hides out in the wreckage of the destroyed pesticide factory, banging on pipes to scare away snakes, marveling at the view of the slum surrounding him, this reader shrank at the idea of what he was breathing, touching, consuming, and yet none of the inhabitants of the "Nutcracker" (the slum of Khaufpur) can stop inhaling, drinking, touching, living poisons. This novel is in part about how life continues, misshapen, when the force of catastrophe has irreparably marred a community and its people. Their rage and their struggle is a shaping force in this novel, in part because Animal's own voice (his cynicism, frustrations, schizophrenic thoughts, despair, and agonizing hope) communicates it so potently.<br /><br />I would love to teach this novel in a course about environmental catastrophe because part of what the novel does is confront the ruptures in the contract with the world that are exposed by a tragedy such as this one. Though the pesticide disaster reaches mythological proportions (causing Animal to muse on death goddess Kali roaming the streets), it is not mythological or cyclical; this is negligence, evil, malfeasance, corruption. The American chemical company responsible for the tragedy does not claim their crimes, performed as they were across the globe, not touching the home bases of the lawyers and corporate tycoons who continue to make deals with local government to dodge responsibility and justice. Animal makes the point that deadly poisoning like this happens all over the world and that "Kampanis" (the locals' word for the chemical company) are difficult to pin down--simultaneously everywhere and nowhere. This is why Zafar, the radical leader who befriends Animal, hopes that the power of nothing will give the people of Khaufpur some power over these leaders; while they are locatable, discrete individuals, without the power, the money, or the influence to defend themselves, they also have nothing at all to lose--and much despair and anger to articulate and perform.<br /><br />I loved the vividness of this novel. It unshirkingly details the horrifying results of "that night" when the pesticide gas killed thousands of people. It juxtaposes the imagined selfhood of the wealthy white Americans coming in to make a deal with the local government with the way that they disregard the humanity of the impoverished Khaufpuris coughing, miscarrying, dying. The categorization of people, the line between a human and an animal, gets played out in fascinating ways in this novel, both to the detriment of humankind (who always wants to assign someone to the category of animal, not worthy of representation, recognition, speech, or love) and to the exaltation of nature, even in its brokenness (to remember one's connection to the animals, to the world, to place, to nature is to recover something paradisical, the conclusion of the novel implies).<br /><br />I think this review isn't doing the novel justice, and the more I reflect on the novel, the more i think I should have gone with five stars instead of four. The structure is really strange; I found it hard to get into; it's very conversational and anecdotal in the beginning. Sinha unspools his tale slowly; I think he wants the reader to feel what it is like to live in this place and to be surrounded by sickness and madness but also by humor, resilience, and opportunism. Also, Animal's view of himself is so dire that one of the fascinating turns of the novel is his gradual self-articulation as a moral being, which requires a lot of skulking in the muck in the beginning to establish why that gradual achievement of dignity is so remarkable. Finally, I think Sinha did not want the characters to seem simply pitiable, but also real, funny, obscene, competitive, communicative, deceptive--all the tangled things that people are rather than a broad category of "victim" or "hero." (One of my favorite parts of the book is when perhaps the most heroic character, Zafar, ends up laughing about all of Animal's amoral antics. It humanizes him.)<br /><br />After this slow beginning, it caught me off-guard for the last hundred pages or so to feel really urgent and powerful, as Animal's adopted mother, a nun who can only speak her native tongue of French after the Khaufpuri disaster, waits for the Apocalypse and the activists wait to find out if the Kampani will be forced to attend hearings or if they will make a deal before any justice can be sought. I don't want to put any spoilers into my review, but I think the way that Sinha pulled off the ending was particularly impressive because it would be very easy to either sentimentalize or make failure and despair seem inevitable (like a naturalist novel might). It's impossible, however, to write a happy ending because the situation is so terrible and reparations not only not at hand but really scarcely imaginable. The ending that Sinha did right--with allusions to apocalypse and death--both encompasses irreparable tragedy and death and extends the hope for renewal, through a blending of irony and dreamscape, tragic denouements and eleventh hour reprieves.<br /><br />That seemed particularly impressive to me because it's hard to know how to end a novel of environmental catastrophe without somehow denying the possibility that human beings could destroy the pact between themselves and the world (not to mention between each other) and could disrupt the harmony of the spheres. (I'm borrowing both of those ideas from the novel, in which one character says that the world relies on promises and another says that it depends on music. Animal concludes that both could be true, that music is a kind of promise.) To deny the possibility of death and destruction would be to erase Bhopal (or, in this case, Khaufpur) the way that the Kampani would like to. To submit to its inevitability would be to assent to our extinction.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12588995670484625455" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

